In this article, President Barack Obama proclaims October 15, 2015, as Blind Americans Equality Day. He acknowledges the contributions made by blind and visually impaired individuals to the nation and emphasizes the importance of ensuring equal opportunities for them. The article highlights the Americans with Disabilities Act, which has improved accessibility for the blind community. The administration has also hosted the White House Summit on Disability and Employment and focused on improving the accessibility of federal government websites. The inclusion of Braille in schools and the expansion of access to workforce, education, and rehabilitation services for Americans with disabilities are also mentioned. The article concludes by reaffirming the commitment to a society where everyone, including those with disabilities, has an equal shot at the American dream.